{{Unreferenced|date=August 2009}}
{{Arabic-script sidebar}}

'''{{transl|ar|DIN|Ḫāʾ}}''' or '''{{transl|ar|DIN|Khāʾ}}''' ({{lang|ar|خ}}, transliterated as {{transl|ar|DIN|ḫ}} ([[DIN-31635]]), {{transl|ar|Wehr|ḵ}} ([[Hans Wehr transliteration|Hans Wehr]]), {{transl|ar|ALA-LC|kh}} ([[ALA-LC]]) or {{transl|ar|ISO|ẖ}} ([[ISO 233]])), is one of the six letters the [[Arabic alphabet]] added to the twenty-two inherited from the [[Phoenician alphabet]] (the others being {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ṯāʼ]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ḏāl]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ḍād]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ẓāʼ]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ġayn]]}}). It is based on the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ḥāʾ}}''&nbsp; <big>{{lang|ar|[[ح]]}}</big>. It represents the sound {{IPAblink|x}} or {{IPAblink|χ}} in [[Modern Standard Arabic]]. The pronunciation of {{lang|ar|خ}} is very similar to German, Irish, and Polish unpalatalised "[[Ch (digraph)|ch]]", Russian [[Kha (Cyrillic)|х (Cyrillic Kha)]], and Spanish "[[j]]". In name and shape, it is a variant of {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ḥāʾ]]}}. [[South Semitic]] also kept the phoneme separate, and it appears as [[South Arabian alphabet|South Arabian]] [[Image:himjar kha.PNG|14px|ḫ]], [[Ge'ez abugida|Ge'ez]] {{transl|sem|Ḫarm}} ኀ. Its numerical value is 600 (see [[Abjad numerals]]).

When representing this sound in transliteration of Arabic into Hebrew, it is written as ח׳.

The most common transliteration in English is "kh", e.g. '''Khartoum''' ({{lang|ar|الخرطوم}} ''al-Kharṭūm''), '''sheikh''' ({{lang|ar|شيخ}}).

''{{transl|ar|DIN|Ḫāʾ}}'' is written is several ways depending in its position in the word:

{{Arabic alphabet shapes|خ}}

