{{Other uses|GAF (disambiguation)}}
{{SpecialChars}}
[[File:Pashto Gaf.png|thumbnail|The Gaf of [[Pashto alphabet]]]]
[[Image:Gaf.svg|120px|thumb|One form of gaf]]
{{Arabic-script sidebar|Persian}}
{{Arabic alphabet}}
'''Gaf''', or '''gāf''', can be the name of different [[Perso-Arabic alphabet|Perso-Arabic letters]], all representing {{IPAslink|ɡ}}. They are all forms of the letter [[Kaph|kāf]], with additional [[diacritic]]s, such as dots and lines. There are four forms, each used in different places:

* {{big|{{script/Arabic|گ}}}} in [[Perso-Arabic alphabet|Perso-Arabic]] 
* {{big|{{script/Arabic|ݢ}}}} in the [[Jawi script]]
* {{big|{{script/Arabic|ࢴ}}}} in the [[Pegon script]]
* {{big|{{script/Arabic|ݣ}}}} or {{big|{{script/Arabic|ڭ}}}} in Moroccan, occidental Algerian, and many Berber languages
*{{big|{{script/Arabic|ګ}}}} in [[Pashto language|Pashto]]
* {{big|{{script/Arabic|[[ڳ]]}}}} in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] and [[Saraiki language|Saraiki]]

Note that in Arabic dialects like [[Hejazi Arabic|Hejazi]] and [[Najdi Arabic|Najdi]] the {{big|{{script/Arabic|ق}}}} is used instead to represent the phoneme {{IPAslink|ɡ}} (instead of the Classical {{IPAslink|q}}), so the name gāf (instead of qāf) can be used for the letter when trying to explain a pronunciation or a spelling of a word, whether the word is foreign or dialectal. 

== Gaf with line ==

{{big|{{script/Arabic|گ}}}} is based on kāf with an additional line. It is rarely used in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] itself, but may be used to represent the sound {{IPAslink|ɡ}} when writing other languages.
It is frequently used in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Pashto language|Pashto]], [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]], [[Urdu]] and [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] and is one of four Perso-Arabic letters not found in Arabic.

{{big|{{script/Arabic|ڭ}}}} can also be used to represent {{IPAslink|ɡ}} in [[Morocco]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}}
{{Arabic alphabet shapes|گ}}

== Gaf with single dot above ==

{{big|{{script/Arabic|ݢ}}}} is derived from a variant form ({{big|{{script/Arabic|ک}}}}) of kāf with the addition of a [[dot (diacritic)|dot]]. It is not used in the [[Arabic language]] itself, but is used in the [[Jawi script]] of [[Malay language|Malay]] to represent a [[voiced velar stop]] {{IPAslink|ɡ}}. [[Unicode]] includes two forms on this letter: one based on the standard Arabic kāf, {{big|{{script/Arabic|ك}}}}, and one based on the variant form {{big|{{script/Arabic|ک}}}}. The latter is the preferred form.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2003/03176-gafs.pdf|author=Jonatha Kew|title=Proposal to encode Jawi and Moroccan Arabic GAF characters|date=2003}}</ref>
