== Gaf with line and two dots ==
{{Main article|Gueh}}
{{big|{{script/Arabic|ڳ}}}} is derived from a variant form ({{big|{{script/Arabic|ک}}}}) of kāf with the addition of a line and two dots. It is used in the [[Sindhi alphabet|Sindhi]] and [[Saraiki alphabet|Saraiki]] alphabets.
{{Arabic alphabet shapes|ڳ}}

== Gaf with three dots ==

[[File:Top Floors Cafe Argana in 2006 (Cropped).png|thumb|300px|The Arabic signage for the Argana cafe in Marrakesh's [[Jemaa el-Fnaa]] features a prominent gaf with three dots.]]
{{big|{{script/Arabic|ݣ}}}} or {{big|{{script/Arabic|ڭ}}}} is based on a variant form ({{big|{{script/Arabic|ك}}}}) of kāf with the addition of three [[dot (diacritic)|dots]]. It is used in [[Moroccan Arabic]] to represent {{IPAslink|ɡ}}. Examples of its use include city names (such as [[Agadir]] {{script/Arabic|أݣادير}}, also written: {{script/Arabic|أغادير}}) and family names (such as [[Hicham El Guerrouj|El Guerrouj]] {{script/Arabic|الݣروج}}, also written: {{script/Arabic|الكروج}}). 

{{Arabic alphabet shapes|ڭ}}
{{Arabic alphabet shapes|ݣ}}

