{{Orphan|date=January 2016}}
{{update| \ "the article was written from 2011 and 2014 but the field is rapidly advancing"|date=May 2018}}

'''[[Arabic]]''' is one of the major languages that have been given attention by '''[[machine translation]]''' (MT) researchers since the very early days of MT and specifically in the U.S.  The language has always been considered "due to its [[morphology (linguistics)|morphological]], [[syntactic]], [[phonetic]] and [[phonological]] properties [to be] one of the most difficult languages for [[written language|written]] and [[spoken language]] processing."<ref name=TRANSJ>{{cite journal|last=Zughoul|first=Muhammad|author2=Abu-Alshaar, Awatef|title=English/Arabic/English Machine Translation: A Historical Perspective|journal=Translators' Journal|date=3 August 2005|volume=50|issue=3|pages=1022–1041|url=http://id.erudit.org/iderudit/011612ar|accessdate=2 June 2011}}</ref>

Arabic "differs tremendously in terms of its [[character (symbol)|characters]], morphology and [[diacritic|diacritization]] from other languages."<ref name=TRANSJ /> Accordingly, researchers cannot always import solutions from other languages, and today Arabic machine translation still needs more efforts to be improved, mainly in the area of semantic representation systems, which are essential for achieving high quality translation.

== Approaches for the study of machine processing of Arabic ==

=== Particularistic approaches ===
Particularistic approaches describe the linguistic features of Arabic and use them for a local processing approach specific to the internal linguistic system of Arabic. They are concerned with the morphological and semantic aspects of Arabic. [[Sakhr Software Company|Sakhr]] is one of the Arabic speaking groups developing systematically machine processing of Arabic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arabic Machine Translation|url=http://international.sakhr.com/arabic-machine-translation-MT.html|accessdate=4 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715230846/http://international.sakhr.com/arabic-machine-translation-MT.html|archivedate=15 July 2011|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

=== Universalist approaches ===
[[Universalist]] approaches use the methods and systems  proved to be useful in other languages like [[English language|English]] or [[French language|French]] making some adaptations if necessary. The focus here is on the syntactic aspects of the linguistic system in general. This approach is followed by most of the companies producing [[software application]]s for Arabic.

